Geospatial Risk Prediction of Vandalism and Criminal Mischief in Philadelphia

Michael Clifford

October 19, 2023

1. Introduction

This analysis will attempt to predict the occurrence of “Vandalism/Criminal Mischief” in Philadelphia, PA, using 2021 data. While this crime has tangible effects, i.e. the damage or destruction of property, the reporting of such occurrences may be imbalanced. First, more minor acts of vandalism may not even be noticed if the damage is small or the property owner is an absentee. Second, it could be under reported in areas where property is already in a greater state of disrepair, as residents may be concerned with more serious and more violent crimes. On the flip side, there may be areas where people are especially sensitive to the appearance of their neighborhood and are overzealous in reporting what they consider to be vandalism. In general, what constitutes vandalism may differ from person to person or community to community. To some a may include graffiti of any size, while others may only consider more serious and costly structural damage to constitute vandalism.

## using {sf} to create the grid
## Note the `.[chicagoBoundary] %>% ` line. This is needed to clip the grid to our data
fishnet <- 
  st_make_grid(hoods,
               cellsize = 1640, 
               square = TRUE) %>%
  .[hoods] %>%            # fast way to select intersecting polygons
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(uniqueID = 1:n())
## add a value of 1 to each crime, sum them with aggregate
crime_net <- 
  dplyr::select(mischief) %>% 
  mutate(countMischief = 1) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, sum) %>%
  mutate(countMischief = replace_na(countMischief, 0),
         uniqueID = 1:n(),
         cvID = sample(round(nrow(fishnet) / 24), 
                       size=nrow(fishnet), replace = TRUE))

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = crime_net, aes(fill = countMischief), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  labs(title = "Vandalism/Criminal Mishchief\nFishnet Count\nPhiladelphia - 2021",
       caption = "Figure 3") +
  mapTheme()

Figure 3 shows the count of reported mischief aggregated in a city-wide fishnet.

2. Risk Factors

To help predict the future occurrence of vandalism and criminal mischief in Philadelphia, I will examine some possible risk factors: 311 reports of illegal dumping and abandoned cars, as well as locations of vacant properties. These factors suggest a lack of “eyes on the street” as Jane Jacobs would say, and may designate areas prime for mischievous acts. It should be noted though that reporting for illegal dumping and abandoned cars may be susceptible to the same kinds of reporting bias discussed in the introduction.

## only pulling a single variable for our model to keep it simple

3.The Spatial Process of Mischief

## generates warnings from PROJ issues
## {spdep} to make polygon to neighborhoods... 
final_net.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(final_net), queen=TRUE)
## ... and neighborhoods to list of weigths
final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

# print(final_net.weights, zero.policy=TRUE)
## see ?localmoran
local_morans <- localmoran(final_net$countMischief, final_net.weights, zero.policy=TRUE) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# join local Moran's I results to fishnet
final_net.localMorans <- 
  cbind(local_morans, as.data.frame(final_net)) %>% 
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(Illegal_Dumping, 
                Abandoned_Cars,
                Vacant_Property,
                Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.001, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)
## This is just for plotting
vars <- unique(final_net.localMorans$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(final_net.localMorans, Variable == i), 
              aes(fill = Value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme(title_size = 14) + theme(legend.position="bottom")}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(varList, ncol = 3, top = "Figure 10: Local Morans I statistics, Mischief"))

Figure 10 again shows us the risk factors, as well as the results of the Moran’s I test on vandalism and criminal mischief. As estimated from previous plots, there are significant clusters of reported mischief in the inner core of Philadelphia.

4.Regression Modeling

4.1 Cross-validation Poisson Regression

A cross-validation Poisson Regression is run using illegal dumping, abandoned cars, and vacant properties as predictive variables for vandalism/criminal mischief. This is done both with a random k-fold and by neighborhood grouping.

# View(crossValidate)

## define the variables we want
reg.vars <- c("Illegal_Dumping", "Abandoned_Cars", "Vacant_Property")

## RUN REGRESSIONS
#k-fold
reg.CV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",                           
  dependentVariable = "countMischief",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID, countMischief, Prediction, geometry)

#spatial process
reg.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",                           
  dependentVariable = "countMischief",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countMischief, Prediction, geometry)

reg.summary <- 
  rbind(
    mutate(reg.CV,           Error = Prediction - countMischief,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV"),
    mutate(reg.spatialCV,    Error = Prediction - countMischief,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV")
 ) %>%
    st_sf()

4.2 Accuracy and Generalizability

To determine the accuracy of these models, I first look at the mean average error for each.

# calculate errors by NEIGHBORHOOD
error_by_reg_and_fold <- 
  reg.summary %>%
    group_by(Regression, cvID) %>% 
    summarize(Mean_Error = mean(Prediction - countMischief, na.rm = T),
              MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T),
              SD_MAE = sd(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup()

error_by_reg_and_fold %>%
  #filter(str_detect(Regression, "LOGO")) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = MAE)) +
    facet_wrap(~Regression) +
    scale_fill_viridis() +
    labs(title = "Vandalism/Criminal Mischief errors by Regression",
         caption = "Figure 13") +
    mapTheme() + theme(legend.position="bottom")

Figure 13 shows the mean average error in different parts of the city for the random k-fold and neighborhood-based (Spatial LOGO-CV) regressions. The random k-fold is much more accurate, while the neighborhood-based model shows areas with significant errors, especially in North Philadelphia.

st_drop_geometry(error_by_reg_and_fold) %>%
  group_by(Regression) %>% 
    summarize(Mean_MAE = round(mean(MAE), 2),
              SD_MAE = round(sd(MAE), 2)) %>%
  kable(caption = "Figure 14: Error by Regression") %>%
    kable_styling("striped", full_width = F)
Figure 14: Error by Regression
Regression Mean_MAE SD_MAE
Random k-fold CV 0.83 1.21
Spatial LOGO-CV 3.09 3.32

Figure 14 shows the overall mean average error and standard deviation for both models, again showing that the random k-fold is much more accurate.

To determine the generalizability of each model, I group the outcomes into majority white and non-white areas to see if there is racial bias baked in.

varslist = c("B02001_001E", "B02001_002E")

tracts <-  
  get_acs(geography = "tract",
          variables = varslist, 
          year=2021, state=42,
          county=101, output="wide", geometry=TRUE) %>% 
  st_transform('ESRI:102729')

tracts <- tracts %>% 
  dplyr::select(GEOID, NAME, all_of(varslist))

tracts <- tracts %>%
  rename(TotPop = B02001_001E,  White = B02001_002E) %>%
  mutate(whitePct = White/TotPop)

tracts <-
  tracts %>%
  mutate(raceContext = ifelse(whitePct > 0.5, "Majority White", "Majority Non-White")) %>%
  na.omit()
reg.summary %>% 
    st_centroid() %>%
    st_join(tracts) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      group_by(Regression, raceContext) %>%
      summarize(mean.Error = mean(Error, na.rm = T)) %>%
      spread(raceContext, mean.Error) %>%
      kable(caption = "Figure 15: Mean Error by neighborhood racial context") %>%
        kable_styling("striped", full_width = F)
Figure 15: Mean Error by neighborhood racial context
Regression Majority Non-White Majority White
Random k-fold CV -1.178308 0.5034621
Spatial LOGO-CV -1.187491 0.5147928

Figure 15 shows a racial bias in both models, with underprediction in majority non-white areas and overprediction in majority-white areas.

5. Conclusion

I do not recommend that this algorithm be put into production. First, there was limited exploratory analysis, and there are many more predictive that could be tested and incorporated/substituted. While the random k-fold model was fairly accurate (especially compared to the neighborhood-based model), its generalizability could be improved, and tested for other contexts in addition to race.

There is also the issue of reporting bias as discussed in the introduction. While the random k-fold regression model appears accurate, if the underlying data comes from biased reporting than the model can’t be fully trusted. If vandalism and criminal mischief are in fact over-reported this model may be appropriate, as it understates the risk of mischief compared to the kernel density model. If there are discrepancies in reporting among different communities in the city though this model would not be appropriate, as demonstrated by the racial bias it produces (figure 15). That being said, over-policing of minority areas is a recurring issue, and this model may help mitigate this as it under predicts in in majority non-white areas compared to majority-white ones. I would have to do more research into reporting bias though before reversing my (non)recommendation.
